<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="244" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1042,1212]" pageId="7" pageNumber="244">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,267,1042,1068]" pageId="7" pageNumber="244">Remarks.</emphasis>
In placing this species in 
<taxonomicName authority=", Zhang &amp; Webb (1996)" authorityName=", Zhang &amp; Webb" authorityYear="1996" box="[560,949,1042,1069]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Drabescus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[560,680,1042,1068]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="244">Drabescus</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang, Y. L. &amp; Webb, M. D." box="[695,949,1042,1069]" pageId="7" pageNumber="244" pagination="1 - 103" refId="ref9072" refString="Zhang, Y. L. &amp; Webb, M. D. (1996) A revised classification of the Asian and Pacific Selenocephalinae leafhoppers (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, Entomology Series, 65, 1 - 103." type="journal article" year="1996">Zhang &amp; Webb (1996)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
commented that although differing in head shape from typical 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Zhang &amp; Webb" authorityYear="1996" box="[368,488,1078,1104]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Drabescus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[368,488,1078,1104]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="244">Drabescus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see new species Remarks above) and being smaller (approximately 
<quantity box="[1266,1325,1079,1105]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="244" unit="mm" value="7.0">7mm</quantity>
) the male genitalia of two males, similar to the female 
<typeStatus box="[644,747,1114,1140]" pageId="7" pageNumber="244">lectotype</typeStatus>
(all three from the 
<collectingCountry box="[959,1090,1114,1141]" name="Philippines" pageId="7" pageNumber="244">Philippines</collectingCountry>
), were typical of the genus (see 
<figureCitation box="[151,219,1150,1176]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1695,1720]" captionTargetBox="[229,1374,195,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[189,1398,187,1685]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Drabescus sp. A–F, D. nitens (Stål), female type; A–B, habitus, dorsal and lateral view respectively; C, head and thorax, dorsal view; D, face; E, forewing; F, abdominal terminalia, lateral view; G–N, Drabescus?nitens (Stål), male (Philippnes, BMNH); G, pygofer and anal tube, lateral view; H, connective, ventral view; I, valve, ventral view; J, subgenital plate, ventral view; K, left style apex, lateral view; L, left style, ventral view; M–N, aedeagus lateral and ventral view, respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3234334/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="244">Figs 3</figureCitation>
G–N). However, as the genitalia of the two males represented two different species, the identity of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Zhang &amp; Webb" authorityYear="1996" box="[1335,1436,1151,1177]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Drabescus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitens">
<emphasis box="[1335,1355,1151,1176]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="244">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1369,1436,1151,1176]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="244">nitens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remains unclear.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
